# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: block-storage
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:block-storage/block-level-storage] Storage in such services is organised as blocks.
[src:block-storage/block-level-storage] This emulates the type of behaviour seen in traditional disks or tape storage through storage virtualization.
[src:block-storage/block-level-storage] Blocks are identified by an arbitrary and assigned identifier by which they may be stored and retrieved, but this has no obvious meaning in terms of files or documents.
[src:block-storage/block-level-storage] A file system must be applied on top of the block-level storage to map 'files' onto a sequence of blocks.
[src:block-storage/block-level-storage] Amazon EBS (elastic block store) is an example of a cloud block store.
[src:block-storage/block-level-storage] Cloud block-level storage will usually offer facilities such as replication for reliability, or backup services.
[src:block-storage/block-level-storage] Block-level storage is in contrast to an object store or 'bucket store', such as Amazon S3 (simple storage service), or to a database.
[src:block-storage/block-level-storage] These operate at a higher level of abstraction and are able to work with entities such as files, documents, images, videos or database records.
[src:block-storage/block-level-storage] Instance stores are another form of cloud-hosted block-level storage.
[src:block-storage/block-level-storage] These are provided as *part of* an 'instance', such as an Amazon EC2 (elastic compute cloud) service.
[src:block-storage/block-level-storage] As EC2 instances are primarily provided as compute resources, rather than storage resources, their storage is less robust.
[src:block-storage/block-level-storage] Their contents will be lost if the cloud instance is stopped.
[src:block-storage/block-level-storage] As these stores are part of the instance's virtual server they offer higher performance and bandwidth to the instance.
[src:block-storage/block-level-storage] They are best used for temporary storage such as caching or temporary files, with persistent storage held on a different type of server.
[src:block-storage/block-level-storage] At one time, block-level storage was provided by storage area networks (SAN), and network-attached storage (NAS) provided file-level storage.
[src:block-storage/block-level-storage] With the shift from on-premises hosting to cloud services, this distinction has shifted.
[src:block-storage/block-level-storage] Even block-storage is now seen as distinct servers (thus NAS), rather than the previous array of bare disks.
[src:block-storage/disk-array] A **disk array** is a disk storage system which contains multiple disk drives.
[src:block-storage/disk-array] It is differentiated from a disk enclosure, in that an array has cache memory and advanced functionality, like RAID, deduplication, encryption and virtualization.
[src:block-storage/disk-array] Typically a disk array provides increased availability, resiliency, and maintainability by using additional redundant components (controllers, power supplies, fans, etc.), often up to the point where all single points of failure (SPOFs) are eliminated from the design.
[src:block-storage/disk-array] Additionally, disk array components are often hot-swappable.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] In computer storage, **logical volume management** (**LVM**) provides a method of allocating space on mass-storage devices that is more flexible than conventional partitioning schemes to store volumes.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] In particular, a volume manager can concatenate, stripe together or otherwise combine partitions (or block devices in general) into larger virtual partitions that administrators can re-size or move, potentially without interrupting system use.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] Volume management represents just one of many forms of storage virtualization; its implementation takes place in a layer in the device-driver stack of an operating system (OS) (as opposed to within storage devices or in a network).
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] Most volume-manager implementations share the same basic design.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] They start with **physical volumes** (PVs), which can be either hard disks, hard disk partitions, or logical unit numbers (LUNs) of an external storage device.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] Volume management treats each PV as being composed of a sequence of chunks called **physical extents** (PEs).
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] Some volume managers (such as that in HP-UX and Linux) have PEs of a uniform size; others (such as that in Veritas) have variably-sized PEs that can be split and merged at will.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] Normally, PEs simply map one-to-one to **logical extents** (LEs).
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] With mirroring, multiple PEs map to each LE.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] These PEs are drawn from a **physical volume group** (PVG), a set of same-sized PVs which act similarly to hard disks in a RAID 1 array.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] PVGs are usually laid out so that they reside on different disks or data buses for maximum redundancy.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] The system pools LEs into a *volume group* (VG).
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] The pooled LEs can then be concatenated together into virtual disk partitions called **logical volumes** or LVs.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] Systems can use LVs as raw block devices just like disk partitions: creating mountable file systems on them, or using them as swap storage.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] Striped LVs allocate each successive LE from a different PV; depending on the size of the LE, this can improve performance on large sequential reads by bringing to bear the combined read-throughput of multiple PVs.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] Administrators can grow LVs (by concatenating more LEs) or shrink them (by returning LEs to the pool).
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] The concatenated LEs do not have to be contiguous.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] This allows LVs to grow without having to move already-allocated LEs.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] Some volume managers allow the re-sizing of LVs in either direction while online.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] Changing the size of the LV does not necessarily change the size of a file system on it; it merely changes the size of its containing space.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] A file system that can be resized online is recommended in that it allows the system to adjust its storage on-the-fly without interrupting applications.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] PVs and LVs cannot be shared between or span different VGs (although some volume managers may allow moving them at will between VGs on the same host).
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] This allows administrators conveniently to bring VGs online, to take them offline or to move them between host systems as a single administrative unit.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] VGs can grow their storage pool by absorbing new PVs or shrink by retracting from PVs.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] This may involve moving already-allocated LEs out of the PV.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] Most volume managers can perform this movement online; if the underlying hardware is hot-pluggable this allows engineers to upgrade or replace storage without system downtime.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] A hybrid volume is any volume that intentionally and opaquely makes use of two separate physical volumes.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] For instance, a workload may consist of random seeks so an SSD may be used to permanently store frequently used or recently written data, while using higher-capacity rotational magnetic media for long-term storage of rarely needed data.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] On Linux, bcache or dm-cache may be used for this purpose, while Fusion Drive may be used on OS X.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] ZFS also implements this functionality at the file system level, by allowing administrators to configure multi-level read/write caching.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] Hybrid volumes present a similar concept as hybrid drives, which also combine solid-state storage and rotational magnetic media.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] Some volume managers also implement snapshots by applying copy-on-write to each LE.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] In this scheme, the volume manager will copy the LE to a *copy-on-write table* just before it is written to.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] This preserves an old version of the LV, the snapshot, which may be later reconstructed by overlaying the copy-on-write table atop the current LV.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] Unless the volume management supports both thin provisioning and discard, once an LE in the origin volume is written to, it is permanently stored in the snapshot volume.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] If the snapshot volume was made smaller than its origin, which is a common practice, this may render the snapshot inoperable.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] Snapshots can be useful for backing up self-consistent versions of volatile data such as table files from a busy database, or for rolling back large changes (such as an operating system upgrade) in a single operation.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] Snapshots have a similar effect as rendering storage quiescent, and are similar to the shadow copy (VSS) service in Microsoft Windows.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] Some Linux-based Live CDs also use snapshots to simulate read-write access to a read-only optical disc.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] Refers to PEs as PPs (physical partitions), and to LEs as LPs (logical partitions).
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] Does not have a copy-on-write snapshot mechanism; creates snapshots by freezing one volume of a mirror pair.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] The FreeBSD fast file system (UFS) supports snapshots.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] NetBSD from version 6.0 supports its own re-implementation of Linux LVM.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] Re-implementation is based on a BSD licensed device-mapper driver and uses a port of Linux lvm tools as the userspace part of LVM.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] There is no need to support RAID5 in LVM because of NetBSD superior RAIDFrame subsystem.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] Refers to PVs as volumes (which can be combined with RAID0, RAID1 or RAID5 primitives into larger volumes), to LVs as soft partitions (which are contiguous extents placeable anywhere on volumes, but which cannot span multiple volumes), and to VGs as disk sets.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] Does not have a concept of PEs or LEs; can only RAID0, RAID1, RAID5 or concatenate disk partitions into larger volumes; file systems must span whole volumes.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] ; Software-based RAID is provided by AppleRAID.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] Logical volumes can suffer from external fragmentation when the underlying storage devices do not allocate their PEs contiguously.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] This can reduce I/O performance on slow-seeking media such as magnetic disks and other rotational media.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] Volume managers that use fixed-size PEs, however, typically make PEs relatively large (for example, Linux LVM uses 4 MB by default) in order to amortize the cost of these seeks.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] With implementations that are solely volume management, such as Core Storage and Linux LVM, separating and abstracting away volume management from the file system loses the ability to easily make storage decisions for particular files or directories.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] For example, if a certain directory (but not the entire file system) is to be permanently moved to faster storage, both the file system layout and the underlying volume management layer need to be traversed.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] For example, on Linux it would be needed to manually determine the offset of a file's contents within a file system and then manually *`pvmove`* the extents (along with data not related to that file) to the faster storage.
[src:block-storage/logical-volume-management] Having volume and file management implemented within the same subsystem, instead of having them implemented as separate subsystems, makes the overall process theoretically simpler.
[src:block-storage/raid] RAID levels are distinguished by the amount of redundancy they afford and the minimum number of drives they require, as well as by their relative complexity, performance, energy efficiency, fault tolerance, and availability.
[src:block-storage/raid] The definitive techniques used by RAID were conceived in the 1970s and 1980s: data striping to improve read/write efficiency, and disk mirroring or parity drives for data recovery.
[src:block-storage/raid] With the exception of RAID 1, all of the standard RAID levels use storage virtualization to abstract multiple storage devices into one logical storage volume.
[src:block-storage/raid] In its original coinage, *RAID* is an acronym for **redundant array of inexpensive disks**.
[src:block-storage/raid] 1992) later redefined the acronym to mean **redundant array of independent disks**.
[src:block-storage/raid] Before the advent of data striping and redundant, online disks, it was common for high-capacity, high-availability data storage to rely on so-called SLEDs ("single, large, expensive disks") connected to mainframe computers.
[src:block-storage/raid] RAID has been deployed not only in mainframe computers, but in personal computers, supercomputers, file servers, database servers, web servers, and network-attached storage appliances.
[src:block-storage/raid] The term *RAID* was coined by David Patterson, Garth Gibson, and Randy Katz at the University of California, Berkeley in 1987.
[src:block-storage/raid] Industry manufacturers later redefined the RAID acronym to stand for "redundant array of *independent* disks".
[src:block-storage/raid] RAID modularizes secondary storage by assigning a role to each storage device in a disk array.
[src:block-storage/raid] The array's RAID level is defined by the roles and relationships of these constituent devices.
[src:block-storage/raid] Some RAID levels use parity data to increase fault tolerance.
[src:block-storage/raid] Most parity data is calculated using XOR, but RAID 6 uses addition and multiplication in a particular Galois field or Reed–Solomon error correction.
[src:block-storage/raid] RAID can also provide data security with solid-state drives (SSDs) without the expense of an all-SSD system.
[src:block-storage/raid] For example, a fast SSD can be mirrored with a slower, mechanical hard-disk drive.
[src:block-storage/raid] For this configuration to provide a significant speed advantage, an appropriate controller is needed that uses the fast SSD for all read operations.
[src:block-storage/raid] Originally, there were five standard levels of RAID, but many variations have evolved, including several nested levels and many non-standard levels (mostly proprietary).
[src:block-storage/raid] By contrast, a spanned volume, which stores files sequentially, loses data stored on the failed drive but preserves data stored on the remaining drives.
[src:block-storage/raid] However, recovering the files after drive failure can be challenging and often depends on the specifics of the filesystem.
[src:block-storage/raid] Regardless, files that span onto or off a failed drive will be permanently lost.
[src:block-storage/raid] The cost is increased vulnerability to drive failures—since any drive in a RAID 0 setup failing causes the entire volume to be lost, the average failure rate of the volume rises with the number of attached drives.
[src:block-storage/raid] This makes RAID 0 a poor choice for scenarios requiring data reliability or fault tolerance.
[src:block-storage/raid] In what was originally termed *hybrid RAID*, many storage controllers allow RAID levels to be nested.
[src:block-storage/raid] The elements of a *RAID* may be either individual drives or arrays themselves.
[src:block-storage/raid] Arrays are rarely nested more than one level deep.
[src:block-storage/raid] The final array is known as the top array.
[src:block-storage/raid] When the top array is RAID 0 (such as in RAID 1+0 and RAID 5+0), most vendors omit the "+" (yielding RAID 10 and RAID 50, respectively).
[src:block-storage/raid] Many configurations other than the basic numbered RAID levels are possible, and many companies, organizations, and groups have created their own non-standard configurations, in many cases designed to meet the specialized needs of a small niche group.
[src:block-storage/raid] The distribution of data across multiple drives can be managed either by dedicated computer hardware or by software.
[src:block-storage/raid] A software solution may be part of the operating system, part of the firmware and drivers supplied with a standard drive controller (so-called "hardware-assisted software RAID"), or it may reside entirely within the hardware RAID controller.
[src:block-storage/raid] Hardware RAID controllers can be configured through card BIOS or Option ROM before an operating system is booted, and after the operating system is booted, proprietary configuration utilities are available from the manufacturer of each controller.
[src:block-storage/raid] Software RAID implementations are provided by many modern operating systems.
[src:block-storage/raid] If a boot drive fails, the system has to be sophisticated enough to be able to boot from the remaining drive or drives.
[src:block-storage/raid] For instance, consider a computer whose disk is configured as RAID 1 (mirrored drives); if the first drive in the array fails, then a first-stage boot loader might not be sophisticated enough to attempt loading the second-stage boot loader from the second drive as a fallback.
[src:block-storage/raid] The second-stage boot loader for FreeBSD is capable of loading a kernel from such an array.
[src:block-storage/raid] Software-implemented RAID is not always compatible with the system's boot process, and it is generally impractical for desktop versions of Windows.
[src:block-storage/raid] However, hardware RAID controllers are expensive and proprietary.
[src:block-storage/raid] To fill this gap, inexpensive "RAID controllers" were introduced that do not contain a dedicated RAID controller chip, but simply a standard drive controller chip, or the chipset built-in RAID function, with proprietary firmware and drivers.
[src:block-storage/raid] During early bootup, the RAID is implemented by the firmware and, once the operating system has been more completely loaded, the drivers take over control.
[src:block-storage/raid] Consequently, such controllers may not work when driver support is not available for the host operating system.
[src:block-storage/raid] An example is Intel Rapid Storage Technology, implemented on many consumer-level motherboards.
[src:block-storage/raid] Because some minimal hardware support is involved, this implementation is also called "hardware-assisted software RAID", "hybrid model" RAID, or even "fake RAID".
[src:block-storage/raid] If RAID 5 is supported, the hardware may provide a hardware XOR accelerator.
[src:block-storage/raid] An advantage of this model over the pure software RAID is that—if using a redundancy mode—the boot drive is protected from failure (due to the firmware) during the boot process even before the operating system's drivers take over.
[src:block-storage/raid] Data scrubbing (referred to in some environments as *patrol read*) involves periodic reading and checking by the RAID controller of all the blocks in an array, including those not otherwise accessed.
[src:block-storage/raid] Data scrubbing checks for bad blocks on each storage device in an array, but also uses the redundancy of the array to recover bad blocks on a single drive and to reassign the recovered data to spare blocks elsewhere on the drive.
[src:block-storage/raid] Consequently, using consumer-marketed drives with RAID can be risky, and so-called "enterprise class" drives limit this error recovery time to reduce risk.
[src:block-storage/raid] Western Digital's desktop drives used to have a specific fix.
[src:block-storage/raid] A utility called WDTLER.exe limited a drive's error recovery time.
[src:block-storage/raid] The utility enabled TLER (time limited error recovery), which limits the error recovery time to seven seconds.
[src:block-storage/raid] Around September 2009, Western Digital disabled this feature in their desktop drives (such as the Caviar Black line), making such drives unsuitable for use in RAID configurations.
[src:block-storage/raid] However, Western Digital enterprise class drives are shipped from the factory with TLER enabled.
[src:block-storage/raid] Similar technologies are used by Seagate, Samsung, and Hitachi.
[src:block-storage/raid] For non-RAID usage, an enterprise class drive with a short error recovery timeout that cannot be changed is therefore less suitable than a desktop drive.
[src:block-storage/raid] In late 2010, the Smartmontools program began supporting the configuration of ATA Error Recovery Control, allowing the tool to configure many desktop class hard drives for use in RAID setups.
[src:block-storage/raid] While RAID may protect against physical drive failure, the data is still exposed to operator, software, hardware, and virus destruction.
[src:block-storage/raid] Many studies cite operator fault as a common source of malfunction, such as a server operator replacing the incorrect drive in a faulty RAID, and disabling the system (even temporarily) in the process.
[src:block-storage/raid] An array can be overwhelmed by catastrophic failure that exceeds its recovery capacity and the entire array is at risk of physical damage by fire, natural disaster, and human forces, however backups can be stored off site.
[src:block-storage/raid] An array is also vulnerable to controller failure because it is not always possible to migrate it to a new, different controller without data loss.
[src:block-storage/raid] In practice, the drives are often the same age (with similar wear) and subject to the same environment.
[src:block-storage/raid] Since many drive failures are due to mechanical issues (which are more likely on older drives), this violates the assumptions of independent, identical rate of failure amongst drives; failures are in fact statistically correlated.
[src:block-storage/raid] In practice, the chances for a second failure before the first has been recovered (causing data loss) are higher than the chances for random failures.
[src:block-storage/raid] The probability of two failures in the same 10-hour period was twice as large as predicted by an exponential distribution.
[src:block-storage/raid] An avoidable mode of correlated disk failure is the *batch-correlated disk failure*, in which the array is built out of disks from the same batch and ends up with disks failing in quick succession.
[src:block-storage/raid] Such events are rare but not unheard of.
[src:block-storage/raid] The standard recommendation is to mix disks from different batches, possibly different manufacturers.
[src:block-storage/raid] A 2021 study describes the batch-correlated failure patterns in multiple SSD-based datacenters at Alibaba, where 88.6% of nodes with at least 2 SSDs are using the same model.
[src:block-storage/raid] Another source of correlated disk failure lies not in the disk, but in the interconnects, CPU, or memory.
[src:block-storage/raid] (2008) showed that only 20–55% of storage system failures were due to disks.
[src:block-storage/raid] These parts also have a bursty, correlated failure mode.
[src:block-storage/raid] Unrecoverable read errors (URE) present as sector read failures, also known as latent sector errors (LSE).
[src:block-storage/raid] The associated media assessment measure, unrecoverable bit error (UBE) rate, is typically guaranteed to be less than one bit in 1015 for enterprise-class drives (SCSI, FC, SAS or SATA), and less than one bit in 1014 for desktop-class drives (IDE/ATA/PATA or SATA).
[src:block-storage/raid] Increasing drive capacities and large RAID 5 instances have led to the maximum error rates being insufficient to guarantee a successful recovery, due to the high likelihood of such an error occurring on one or more remaining drives during a RAID set rebuild.
[src:block-storage/raid] When rebuilding, parity-based schemes such as RAID 5 are particularly prone to the effects of UREs as they affect not only the sector where they occur, but also reconstructed blocks using that sector for parity computation.
[src:block-storage/raid] Double-protection parity-based schemes, such as RAID 6, attempt to address this issue by providing redundancy that allows double-drive failures; as a downside, such schemes suffer from elevated write penalty—the number of times the storage medium must be accessed during a single write operation.
[src:block-storage/raid] Schemes that duplicate (mirror) data in a drive-to-drive manner, such as RAID 1 and RAID 10, have a lower risk from UREs than those using parity computation or mirroring between striped sets.
[src:block-storage/raid] Data scrubbing, as a background process, can be used to detect and recover from UREs, effectively reducing the risk of them happening during RAID rebuilds and causing double-drive failures.
[src:block-storage/raid] The behavior of the RAID implementation on encountering on a rebuild also matters.
[src:block-storage/raid] Some implementations *puncture* the array when a URE is encountered, marking the sector/block as inaccessible but continuing with the rebuild.
[src:block-storage/raid] Drive capacity has grown at a much faster rate than transfer speed, and error rates have only fallen a little in comparison.
[src:block-storage/raid] Therefore, larger-capacity drives may take hours if not days to rebuild, during which time other drives may fail or yet undetected read errors may surface.
[src:block-storage/raid] The rebuild time is also limited if the entire array is still in operation at reduced capacity.
[src:block-storage/raid] Given an array with only one redundant drive (which applies to RAID levels 3, 4 and 5, and to "classic" two-drive RAID 1), a second drive failure would cause complete failure of the array.
[src:block-storage/raid] Even though individual drives' mean time between failure (MTBF) have increased over time, this increase has not kept pace with the increased storage capacity of the drives.
[src:block-storage/raid] The time to rebuild the array after a single drive failure, as well as the chance of a second failure during a rebuild, have increased over time.
[src:block-storage/raid] Some commentators have declared that RAID 6 is only a "band aid" in this respect, because it only kicks the problem a little further down the road.
[src:block-storage/raid] However, according to the 2006 NetApp study of Berriman et al., the chance of failure decreases by a factor of about 3,800 (relative to RAID 5) for a proper implementation of RAID 6, even when using commodity drives.
[src:block-storage/raid] Nevertheless, if the currently observed technology trends remain unchanged, in 2019 a RAID 6 array will have the same chance of failure as its RAID 5 counterpart had in 2010.
[src:block-storage/raid] Mirroring schemes such as RAID 10 have a bounded recovery time as they require the copy of a single failed drive, compared with parity schemes such as RAID 6, which require the copy of all blocks of the drives in an array set.
[src:block-storage/raid] Triple parity schemes, or triple mirroring, have been suggested as one approach to improve resilience to an additional drive failure during this large rebuild time.
[src:block-storage/raid] A system crash or other interruption of a write operation can result in states where the parity is inconsistent with the data due to non-atomicity of the write process, such that the parity cannot be used for recovery in the case of a disk failure.
[src:block-storage/raid] This is commonly termed the *write hole* which is a known data corruption issue in older and low-end RAIDs, caused by interrupted destaging of writes to disk.
[src:block-storage/raid] Write hole is a poorly understood and rarely mentioned failure mode for redundant storage systems that do not utilize transactional features.
[src:block-storage/raid] Database researcher Jim Gray wrote "Update in Place is a Poison Apple" during the early days of relational database commercialization.
[src:block-storage/raid] There are concerns about write-cache reliability, specifically regarding devices equipped with a write-back cache, which is a caching system that reports the data as written as soon as it is written to cache, as opposed to when it is written to the non-volatile storage medium.
[src:block-storage/raid] If the system experiences a power loss or other major failure, the data may be irrevocably lost from the cache before reaching the non-volatile storage.
[src:block-storage/raid] For this reason good write-back cache implementations include mechanisms, such as redundant battery power, to preserve cache contents across system failures (including power failures) and to flush the cache at system restart time.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] A **solid-state drive** (**SSD**) is a type of solid-state storage device that uses integrated circuits to store data persistently.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] It is sometimes called **semiconductor storage device**, **solid-state device**, or **solid-state disk**.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Etymologically, "solid-state drive" partly refers to existing data storage devices like tape drives and hard disk drives, which all used a mechanically driven storage medium.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] SSDs rely on non-volatile memory, typically NAND flash, to store data in memory cells.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] The performance and endurance of SSDs vary depending on the number of bits stored per cell, ranging from high-performing single-level cells (SLC) to more affordable but slower quad-level cells (QLC).
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] In addition to flash-based SSDs, other technologies such as 3D XPoint offer faster speeds and higher endurance through different data storage mechanisms.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Unlike traditional hard disk drives (HDDs), SSDs have no moving parts, allowing them to deliver faster data access speeds, reduced latency, increased resistance to physical shock, lower power consumption, and silent operation.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Often interfaced to a system in the same way as HDDs, SSDs are used in a variety of devices, including personal computers, enterprise servers, and mobile devices.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] However, SSDs are generally more expensive on a per-gigabyte basis and have a finite number of write cycles, which can lead to data loss over time.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Despite these limitations, SSDs are increasingly replacing HDDs, especially in performance-critical applications and as primary storage in many consumer devices.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] SSDs come in various form factors and interface types, including SATA, PCIe, and NVMe, each offering different levels of performance.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Hybrid storage solutions, such as solid-state hybrid drives (SSHDs), combine SSD and HDD technologies to offer improved performance at a lower cost than pure SSDs.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] An SSD stores data in semiconductor cells, with its properties varying according to the number of bits stored in each cell (between 1 and 4).
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Single-level cells (SLC) store one bit of data per cell and provide higher performance and endurance.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] In contrast, multi-level cells (MLC), triple-level cells (TLC), and quad-level cells (QLC) store more data per cell but have lower performance and endurance.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] SSDs using 3D XPoint technology, such as Intel's Optane, store data by changing electrical resistance instead of storing electrical charges in cells, which can provide faster speeds and longer data persistence compared to conventional flash memory.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] SSDs based on NAND flash slowly leak charge when not powered, while heavily used consumer drives may start losing data typically after one to two years unpowered in storage.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] SSDs have a limited lifetime number of writes, and also slow down as they reach their full storage capacity.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] SSDs also have internal parallelism that allows them to manage multiple operations simultaneously, which enhances their performance.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Unlike HDDs and similar electromechanical magnetic storage, SSDs do not have moving mechanical parts, which provides advantages such as resistance to physical shock, quieter operation, and faster access times.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Their lower latency results in higher input/output rates (IOPS) than HDDs.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Some SSDs are combined with traditional hard drives in hybrid configurations, such as Intel's Hystor and Apple's Fusion Drive.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] These drives use both flash memory and spinning magnetic disks in order to improve the performance of frequently accessed data.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] SATA and SAS) and standard HDD form factors allow such SSDs to be used as drop-in replacements for HDDs in computers and other devices.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Newer form factors such as mSATA, M.2, U.2, NF1/M.3/NGFF, XFM Express (*Crossover Flash Memory*, form factor XT2) and EDSFF and higher speed interfaces such as NVM Express (NVMe) over PCI Express (PCIe) can further increase performance over HDD performance.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Traditional HDD benchmarks tend to focus on the performance characteristics such as rotational latency and seek time.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] As SSDs do not need to spin or seek to locate data, they are vastly superior to HDDs in such tests.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] However, SSDs have challenges with mixed reads and writes, and their performance may degrade over time.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Therefore, SSD testing typically looks at when the full drive is first used, as the new and empty drive may have much better write performance than it would show after only weeks of use.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] The reliability of both HDDs and SSDs varies greatly among models.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Some field failure rates indicate that SSDs are significantly more reliable than HDDs.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] However, SSDs are sensitive to sudden power interruption, sometimes resulting in aborted writes or even cases of the complete loss of the drive.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Most of the advantages of solid-state drives over traditional hard drives are due to their ability to access data completely electronically instead of electromechanically, resulting in superior transfer speeds and mechanical ruggedness.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] On the other hand, hard disk drives offer significantly higher capacity for their price.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] In traditional HDDs, a rewritten file will generally occupy the same location on the disk surface as the original file, whereas in SSDs the new copy will often be written to different NAND cells for the purpose of wear leveling.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] The wear-leveling algorithms are complex and difficult to test exhaustively.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] As a result, one major cause of data loss in SSDs is firmware bugs.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] While both memory cards and most SSDs use flash memory, they have very different characteristics, including power consumption, performance, size, and reliability.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Originally, solid state drives were shaped and mounted in the computer like hard drives.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] In contrast, memory cards (such as Secure Digital (SD), CompactFlash (CF), and many others) were originally designed for digital cameras and later found their way into cell phones, gaming devices, GPS units, etc.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Most memory cards are physically smaller than SSDs, and designed to be inserted and removed repeatedly.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] SSDs have different failure modes from traditional magnetic hard drives.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Because solid-state drives contain no moving parts, they are generally not subject to mechanical failures.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] However, other types of failures can occur.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] For example, incomplete or failed writes due to sudden power loss may be more problematic than with HDDs, and the failure of a single chip may result in the loss of all data stored on it.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Nonetheless, studies indicate that SSDs are generally reliable, often exceeding their manufacturer-stated lifespan and have lower failure rates than HDDs.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] However, studies also note that SSDs experience higher rates of uncorrectable errors, which can lead to data loss, compared to HDDs.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] The basic parameter for determining the lifespan of Flash-NAND systems is the number of programming-erase (P/E) cycles.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] The TBW parameter is the product of the P/E cycle resource and the SSD capacity.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] For an SSD with a capacity of 1 TB and TBW = 600 TB, the number of P/E cycles is 600.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Recovering data from SSDs presents challenges due to the non-linear and complex nature of data storage in solid-state drives.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] The internal operations of SSDs vary by manufacturer, with commands (e.g.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] TRIM and the ATA Secure Erase) and programs (e.g. hdparm) being able to erase and modify the bits of a deleted file.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] In a distributed computing environment, SSDs can be used as a distributed cache layer that temporarily absorbs the large volume of user requests to slower HDD-based backend storage systems.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] This layer provides much higher bandwidth and lower latency than the storage system would, and can be managed in a number of forms, such as a distributed key-value database and a distributed file system.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] On supercomputers, this layer is typically referred to as burst buffer.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Flash-based solid-state drives can be used to create network appliances from general-purpose personal computer hardware.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] A write protected flash drive containing the operating system and application software can substitute for larger, less reliable disk drives or CD-ROMs.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Appliances built this way can provide an inexpensive alternative to expensive router and firewall hardware.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] SSDs based on an SD card with a live SD operating system are easily write-locked.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Combined with a cloud computing environment or other writable medium, an OS booted from a write-locked SD card is reliable, persistent and impervious to permanent corruption.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] In 2011, Intel introduced a caching mechanism for their Z68 chipset (and mobile derivatives) called Smart Response Technology, which allows a SATA SSD to be used as a cache (configurable as write-through or write-back) for a conventional, magnetic hard disk drive.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] A similar technology is available on HighPoint's RocketHybrid PCIe card.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Solid-state hybrid drives (SSHDs) are based on the same principle, but integrate some amount of flash memory on board of a conventional drive instead of using a separate SSD.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] The flash layer in these drives can be accessed independently from the magnetic storage by the host using ATA-8 commands, allowing the operating system to manage it.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] For example, Microsoft's ReadyDrive technology explicitly stores portions of the hibernation file in the cache of these drives when the system hibernates, making the subsequent resume faster.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Dual-drive hybrid systems are combining the usage of separate SSD and HDD devices installed in the same computer, with overall performance optimization managed by the computer user, or by the computer's operating system software.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Examples of this type of system are bcache and dm-cache on Linux, and Apple's Fusion Drive.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] The primary components of an SSD are the controller and the memory used to store data.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Traditionally, early SSDs used volatile DRAM for storage, but since 2009, most SSDs utilize non-volatile NAND flash memory, which retains data even when powered off.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Flash memory SSDs store data in metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) integrated circuit chips, using non-volatile floating-gate memory cells.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Every SSD includes a controller, which manages the data flow between the NAND memory and the host computer.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] The controller is an embedded processor that runs firmware to optimize performance, managing data, and ensuring data integrity.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] The overall performance of an SSD can scale with the number of parallel NAND chips and the efficiency of the controller.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] For example, controllers that enable parallel processing of NAND flash chips can improve bandwidth and reduce latency.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] The number of flash memory channel increases, the delay of raw flash memory (such as ONFI based NAND flash) decreases, and the bandwidth of raw flash memory increases.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Micron and Intel pioneered faster SSDs by implementing techniques such as data striping and interleaving to enhance read/write speeds.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] More recently, SandForce introduced controllers that incorporate data compression to reduce the amount of data written to the flash memory, potentially increasing both performance and endurance.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Wear leveling is a technique used in SSDs to ensure that write and erase operations are distributed evenly across all blocks of the flash memory.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Without this, specific blocks could wear out prematurely due to repeated use, reducing the overall lifespan of the SSD.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] The process moves data that is infrequently changed (cold data) from heavily used blocks, so that data that changes more frequently (hot data) can be written to those blocks.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] This helps distribute wear more evenly across the entire SSD.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] However, this process introduces additional writes, known as write amplification, which must be managed to balance performance and durability.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Most SSDs use non-volatile NAND flash memory for data storage, primarily due to its cost-effectiveness and ability to retain data without a constant power supply.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] NAND flash-based SSDs store data in semiconductor cells, with the specific architecture influencing performance, endurance, and cost.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Over time, SSD controllers have improved the efficiency of NAND flash, incorporating techniques such as interleaved memory, advanced error correction, and wear leveling to optimize performance and extend the lifespan of the drive.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Lower-end SSDs often use QLC or TLC memory, while higher-end drives for enterprise or performance-critical applications may use MLC or SLC.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] In addition to the flat (planar) NAND structure, many SSDs now use 3D NAND (or V-NAND), where memory cells are stacked vertically, increasing storage density while improving performance and reducing costs.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Some SSDs use volatile DRAM instead of NAND flash, offering very high-speed data access but requiring a constant power supply to retain data.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] DRAM-based SSDs are typically used in specialized applications where performance is prioritized over cost or non-volatility.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Many SSDs, such as NVDIMM devices, are equipped with backup power sources such as internal batteries or external AC/DC adapters.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] These power sources ensure data is transferred to a backup system (usually NAND flash or another storage medium) in the event of power loss, preventing data corruption or loss.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Similarly, ULLtraDIMM devices use components designed for DIMM modules, but only use flash memory, similar to a DRAM SSD.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] DRAM-based SSDs are often used for tasks where data must be accessed at high speeds with low latency, such as in high-performance computing or certain server environments.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] 3D XPoint is a type of non-volatile memory technology developed by Intel and Micron, announced in 2015.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] It operates by changing the electrical resistance of materials in its cells, offering much faster access times than NAND flash.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] 3D XPoint-based SSDs, such as Intel's Optane drives, provide lower latency and higher endurance than NAND-based drives, although they are more expensive per gigabyte.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Drives known as hybrid drives or solid-state hybrid drives (SSHDs) use a hybrid of spinning disks and flash memory.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Some SSDs use magnetoresistive random-access memory (MRAM) for storing data.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Many flash-based SSDs include a small amount of volatile DRAM as a cache, similar to the buffers in hard disk drives.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] This cache can temporarily hold data while it is being written to the flash memory, and it also stores metadata such as the mapping of logical blocks to physical locations on the SSD.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] This cache may also temporarily hold data while it being recently read from the flash memory.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Some SSD controllers, like those from SandForce, achieve high performance without using an external DRAM cache.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] These designs rely on other mechanisms, such as on-chip SRAM, to manage data and minimize power consumption.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Additionally, some SSDs use an SLC buffer mechanism to temporarily store data in single-level cell (SLC) mode, even on multi-level cell (MLC) or triple-level cell (TLC) SSDs.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] This improves write performance by allowing data to be written to faster SLC storage before being moved to slower, higher-capacity MLC or TLC storage.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] On NVMe SSDs, Host Memory Buffer (HMB) technology allows the SSD to use a portion of the system's DRAM instead of relying on a built-in DRAM cache, reducing costs while maintaining a high level of performance.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] In certain high-end consumer and enterprise SSDs, larger amounts of DRAM are included to cache both file table mappings and written data, reducing write amplification and enhances overall performance.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Higher-performing SSDs may include capacitors, supercapacitors or batteries, which helps preserve data integrity in the event of an unexpected power loss.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] The capacitor or battery provides enough power to allow the data in the cache to be written to the non-volatile memory, ensuring no data is lost.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] In some SSDs that use multi-level cell (MLC) flash memory, a potential issue known as "lower page corruption" can occur if power is lost while programming an upper page.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] This can result in previously written data becoming corrupted.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] To address this, some high-end SSDs incorporate supercapacitors to ensure all data can be safely written during a sudden power loss.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Some consumer SSDs have built-in capacitors to save critical data such as the Flash Translation Layer (FTL) mapping table.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Examples include the Crucial M500 and Intel 320 series.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Enterprise-class SSDs, such as the Intel DC S3700 series, often come with more robust power-loss protection mechanisms like supercapacitors or batteries.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] The host interface of an SSD refers to the physical connector and the signaling methods used to communicate between the SSD and the host system.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] This interface is managed by the SSD's controller and is often similar to those found in traditional hard disk drives (HDDs).
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] SSDs may support various logical interfaces, which define the command sets used by operating systems to communicate with the SSD.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] The size and shape of any device are largely driven by the size and shape of the components used to make that device.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Traditional HDDs and optical drives are designed around the rotating platter(s) or optical disc along with the spindle motor inside.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Since an SSD is made up of various interconnected integrated circuits (ICs) and an interface connector, its shape is no longer limited to the shape of rotating media drives.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] The lack of moving parts and light weight meant that an SSD can have no shell and simply appear in the shape of a plug-in board.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] On the other end of the size spectrum, some solid-state storage solutions come in a larger chassis that may even be a rack-mount form factor with numerous SSDs inside.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] They would all connect to a common bus inside the chassis and connect outside the box with a single connector.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] For general computer use, the 2.5-inch form factor (typically found in laptops and used for most SATA SSDs) was the most popular in the 2010s, in three thicknesses (7.0mm, 9.5mm, 14.8 or 15.0mm; with 12.0mm also available for some models).
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] For desktop computers with 3.5-inch hard disk drive slots, a simple adapter plate can be used to make such a drive fit.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Other types of form factors are more common in enterprise applications.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] An SSD can also be completely integrated in the other circuitry of the device, as in the Apple MacBook Air (starting with the fall 2010 model).
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] As of 2014, mSATA and M.2 form factors also gained popularity, primarily in laptops.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] The benefit of using a current HDD form factor would be to take advantage of the extensive infrastructure already in place to mount and connect the drives to the host system.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] These traditional form factors are known by the size of the rotating media (i.e., 5.25-inch, 3.5-inch, 2.5-inch or 1.8-inch) and not the dimensions of the drive casing.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] A *disk-on-a-module* (*DOM*) is a flash drive with either 40/44-pin Parallel ATA (PATA) or SATA interface, intended to be plugged directly into the motherboard and used as a computer hard disk drive (HDD).
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] DOM devices emulate a traditional hard disk drive, resulting in no need for special drivers or other specific operating system support.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] DOMs are usually used in embedded systems, which are often deployed in harsh environments where mechanical HDDs would simply fail, or in thin clients because of small size, low power consumption, and silent operation.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] The most traditional emulates the standard interface, with the 7-pin SATA data connector placed beside the 15-pin SATA power connector.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] An example is the "half-slim SATA" MO-297 size standard.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] To save board space, smaller SATA DOMs were made that only use the SATA data connector.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Supermicro, relied on a separate Berg connector to deliver power.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] A second type of 2012, made by Innodisk, repurposes the 7th pin of the connector from GND to VCC (+5V).
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] A third type called "pin 8 power" replaces the two plastic structural elements on the sides with two metal contacts for GND and VCC.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] These new types of SATADOMs are now so popular that the older 7+15-pin type is virtually not considered to be "SATADOMs" any more, especially as few motherboards provide such an interface.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] There are also USB DOMs designed to be plugging into the USB 2.0 header pins on a motherboard.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] As of 2016, DOM storage capacities range from 4 MB to 128 GB with different variations in physical layouts, including vertical or horizontal orientation.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] For applications where space is at a premium, like for ultrabooks or tablet computers, a few compact form factors were standardized for flash-based SSDs.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] There is the mSATA form factor, which uses the PCI Express Mini Card physical layout.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] It remains electrically compatible with the PCI Express Mini Card interface specification while requiring an additional connection to the SATA host controller through the same connector.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] A higher-performance SSD may use the Mini-PCIe to access the PCIe bus directly.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] M.2 form factor, formerly known as the Next Generation Form Factor (NGFF), is a natural transition from the mSATA and physical layout it used, to a more usable and more advanced form factor.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] While mSATA took advantage of an existing form factor and connector, M.2 has been designed to maximize usage of the card space, while minimizing the footprint.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] The M.2 standard allows both SATA and PCI Express SSDs to be fitted onto M.2 modules.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Before M.2 was standardized, one of the main ways to access the PCIe bus for faster-than-SATA/SAS speed on a server was through the PCIe slot.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] A common shape is called HHHL (Half Height Half Length), or AIC (Add in Card) SSDs.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Some primitive PCIe SSDs do not access the PCIe bus directly, but simply had a PCIe-to-SATA/SAS bridge device and a number of SATA or SAS flash controllers attached.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] This was considered acceptable in 2010, when true PCIe SSDs were still new.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] This shape remains in use for some high performance, high capacity drives.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] The PCIe slot offers 16 lanes of data and 75 watts of power, still much larger than what a M.2 slot can provide.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] It also provides space for a large heat sink.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] There are also adapter boards that converts other form factors, especially M.2 drives with PCIe interface, into regular add-in cards.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] In the early 2000s, a few companies introduced SSDs in Ball Grid Array (BGA) form factors, such as M-Systems' (now SanDisk) DiskOnChip and Silicon Storage Technology's NANDrive (now produced by Greenliant Systems), and Memoright's M1000 for use in embedded systems.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] The main benefits of BGA SSDs are their low power consumption, small chip package size to fit into compact subsystems, and that they can be soldered directly onto a system motherboard to reduce adverse effects from vibration and shock.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Such embedded drives now often adhere to the eMMC and eUFS standards.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Many of the DRAM-based solutions in 2014 use a box that is often designed to fit in a rack-mount system.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] The number of DRAM components required to get sufficient capacity to store the data along with the backup power supplies requires a larger space than traditional HDD form factors.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] The flexibility of the SSD also allows for many unusual form factors, some of which had been important in its early adoption in PCs.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] For example, the SATADIMM from Viking Technology uses an empty DDR3 DIMM slot on the motherboard to provide power to the SSD with a separate SATA connector to provide the data connection back to the computer.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] The result is an easy-to-install SSD with a capacity equal to drives that typically take a full 2.5-inch drive bay.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] The first devices resembling solid-state drives (SSDs) used semiconductor technology, with an early example being the 1978 StorageTek STC 4305.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] This device was a plug-compatible replacement for the IBM 2305 hard drive, initially using charge-coupled devices for storage and later switching to dynamic random-access memory (DRAM).
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] The STC 4305 was significantly faster than its mechanical counterparts and cost around $400,000 for a 45 MB capacity.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Though early SSD-like devices existed, they were not widely used due to their high cost and small storage capacity.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] In the late 1980s, companies like Zitel began selling DRAM-based SSD products under the name "RAMDisk." These devices were primarily used in specialized systems like those made by UNIVAC and Perkin-Elmer.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Top and bottom sides of a 100GB Intel DC S3700 SATA SSD and a 120GB Intel 535 mSATA SSD.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Flash memory, a key component in modern SSDs, was invented in 1980 by Fujio Masuoka at Toshiba.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Flash-based SSDs were patented in 1989 by the founders of SanDisk, which released its first product in 1991: a 20 MB SSD for IBM laptops.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] While the storage capacity was limited and the price high (around $1,000), this marked the beginning of a transition to flash memory as an alternative to traditional hard drives.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] In the 1990s, new manufacturers of flash memory drives emerged, including STEC, Inc., M-Systems, and BiTMICRO.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] As the technology advanced, SSDs saw dramatic improvements in capacity, speed, and affordability.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] By 2016, commercially available SSDs had more capacity than the largest available HDDs.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] By 2018, flash-based SSDs had reached capacities of up to 100 TB in enterprise products, with consumer SSDs offering up to 16 TB.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] These advancements were accompanied by significant increases in read and write speeds, with some high-end consumer models reaching speeds of up to 14.5 GB/s.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] In 2021, NVMe 2.0 with Zoned Namespaces (ZNS) was announced.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] ZNS allows data to be mapped directly to its physical location in memory, providing direct access on an SSD without a flash translation layer.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] In 2024, Samsung announced what it called the world's first SSD with a hybrid PCIe interface, the Samsung 990 EVO.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] The hybrid interface runs in either the x4 PCIe 4.0 or x2 PCIe 5.0 modes, a first for an M.2 SSD.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] SSD prices have also fallen dramatically, with the cost per gigabyte decreasing from around $50,000 in 1991 to less than $0.05 by 2020.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Enterprise flash drives (EFDs) are designed for high-performance applications requiring fast input/output operations per second (IOPS), reliability, and energy efficiency.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] EFDs often have higher specifications than consumer SSDs, making them suitable for mission-critical applications.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] The term was first used by EMC in 2008 to describe SSDs built for enterprise environments.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] One example of an EFD is the Intel DC S3700 series, launched in 2012.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] These drives were notable for their consistent performance, maintaining IOPS variation within a narrow range, which is crucial for enterprise environments.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Another significant product is the Toshiba PX02SS series, launched in 2016.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Designed for write-intensive applications like online transaction processing, these drives achieved impressive read and write speeds and high endurance ratings.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] In 2017, Intel introduced SSDs based on 3D XPoint technology under the Optane brand.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Unlike NAND flash, 3D XPoint uses a different method to store data, offering higher IOPS performance, although sequential read and write speeds remain slower compared to traditional SSDs.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] As SSD technology continues to improve, they are increasingly used in ultra-mobile PCs and lightweight laptop systems.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] The first flash-memory SSD based PC to become available was the Sony Vaio UX90, announced for pre-order on 27 June 2006 and began shipping in Japan on 3 July 2006 with a 16 GB flash memory hard drive.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Another of the first mainstream releases of SSD was the XO Laptop, built as part of the One Laptop Per Child project.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Mass production of these computers, built for children in developing countries, began in December 2007.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] By 2009, Dell, Toshiba, Asus, Apple, and Lenovo had begun producing laptops with SSDs.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] By 2010, Apple's MacBook Air line began using solid state drives as the default.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] In 2011, Intel's Ultrabook became the first widely available consumer computers using SSDs aside from the MacBook Air.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] At present, SSD devices are widely used and distributed by a number of companies, with a small number of companies manufacturing the NAND flash devices within them.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] SSD shipments were approximately 11 million units in 2009, rising to 17.3 million units in 2011 for a total market value of US$5 billion.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Shipments continued to grow to 39 million units in 2012 and were projected to reach 83 million units in 2013, 201.4 million units in 2016, and 227 million units in 2017.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] The global solid-state drive (SSD) market is projected to grow significantly between 2024 and 2030, driven by rising demand for data center expansion, cloud computing services, and consumer electronics upgrades.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] In a 2024 report, Grand View Research estimated the SSD market at USD 19.1 billion in 2023 and projected it to reach USD 55.1 billion by 2030.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] In a separate 2024 study, Mordor Intelligence valued the market at USD 63.45 billion for 2024, forecasting growth to USD 172.82 billion by 2030.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] The same file systems used on hard disk drives can typically also be used on solid state drives.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] File systems that support SSDs generally also support the TRIM command, which helps the SSD to recycle discarded data.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] The file system does not need to manage wear leveling or other flash memory characteristics, as they are handled internally by the SSD.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] F2FS, JFFS2) help to reduce write amplification on SSDs, especially in situations where only very small amounts of data are changed, such as when updating file-system metadata.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] If an operating system does not support using TRIM on discrete swap partitions, it might be possible to use swap files inside an ordinary file system instead.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] For example, macOS does not support swap partitions; it only swaps to files within a file system, so it can use TRIM when, for example, swap files are deleted.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Since 2010, standard Linux drive utilities have taken care of appropriate partition alignment by default.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Kernel support for the TRIM operation was introduced in version 2.6.33 of the Linux kernel mainline, released on 24 February 2010.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] The ext4, Btrfs, XFS, JFS, and F2FS file systems include support for the discard (TRIM or UNMAP) function.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Non-native file systems such as exFAT and NTFS-3G also support TRIM.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] To automatically make use of TRIM on file deletion, a file system must be mounted using the `discard` parameter.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Linux swap partitions are by default performing discard operations when the underlying drive supports TRIM, with the possibility to turn them off.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Support for queued TRIM, a SATA 3.1 feature that results in TRIM commands not disrupting the command queues, was introduced in Linux kernel 3.12, released on November 2, 2013.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] An alternative to the kernel-level TRIM operation is to use a user-space utility called fstrim that goes through all of the unused blocks in a filesystem and dispatches TRIM commands for those areas.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Thefstrimutility is usually run by cron or systemd as a scheduled task.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] A filesystem that supports TRIM remains required.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Whether formatting or resizing trims the unused space depends on the implementation.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] For example, the mke2fs program for formatting ext2/3/4 defaults to issuing a TRIM command (if supported) to the entire block, but the resize2fs program for resizing ext2/3/4 does not TRIM the space left unused after shrinking.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] TRIM-after-resize is instead done by fdisk or sfdisk, programs that edit the partition table.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] In addition, bcache is designed to have an SSD act as a read/write cache for a slower drive such as an HDD.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Versions since Mac OS X 10.6.8 (Snow Leopard) support TRIM but only when used with an Apple-purchased SSD.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] TRIM is not automatically enabled for third-party drives, except for external removable SSDs, although it can be enabled by using third-party utilities such as *Trim Enabler*.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] The status of TRIM can be checked in the System Information application or in the `system_profiler` command-line tool.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Versions since OS X 10.10.4 (Yosemite) include `sudo trimforce enable` as a Terminal command that enables TRIM on non-Apple SSDs.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] There is also a technique to enable TRIM in versions earlier than Mac OS X 10.6.8, although it remains uncertain whether TRIM is actually utilized properly in those cases.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Prior to Windows 7, Microsoft Windows did not take any specific measures to support solid state drives.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] From Windows 7, the standard NTFS file system provides support for the TRIM command.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] By default, Windows 7 and newer versions execute TRIM commands automatically if the device is detected to be a solid-state drive *and* the filesystem driver supports TRIM (NTFS or ReFS).
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] However, because TRIM irreversibly resets all freed space, it may be desirable to disable support where enabling data recovery is preferred over wear leveling.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Windows implements TRIM for more than just file-delete operations.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] The TRIM operation is integrated with partition- and volume-level commands such as *format* and *delete*, with file-system commands relating to truncate and compression, and with the System Restore (also known as Volume Snapshot) feature.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] The SuperFetch feature will also not materially improve performance and causes additional overhead in the system and SSD.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Since Windows 8.1, the Windows Defrag routine would instead "retrim" (TRIM) partitions detected as SSDs.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Windows Vista generally expects hard disk drives rather than SSDs.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Windows Vista includes ReadyBoost to exploit characteristics of USB-connected flash devices, but for SSDs it only improves the default partition alignment to prevent read-modify-write operations that reduce the speed of SSDs.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Most SSDs are typically split into 4 KiB sectors, while earlier systems may be based on 512 byte sectors with their default partition setups unaligned to the 4 KiB boundaries.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Windows Vista does not send the TRIM command to solid-state drives, but some third-party utilities such as SSD Doctor will periodically scan the drive and TRIM the appropriate entries.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Windows 7 and later versions have native support for SSDs.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] The operating system detects the presence of an SSD and optimizes operation accordingly.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] For SSD devices, Windows 7 disables ReadyBoost and automatic defragmentation.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Despite the initial statement by Steven Sinofsky before the release of Windows 7, however, defragmentation is not disabled, even though its behavior on SSDs differs.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] One reason is the low performance of Volume Shadow Copy Service on fragmented SSDs.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] The second reason is to avoid reaching the practical maximum number of file fragments that a volume can handle.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Windows 7 also includes support for the TRIM command to reduce garbage collection for data that the operating system has already determined is no longer valid.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Windows 8.1 and later Windows systems also support automatic TRIM for PCI Express SSDs based on NVMe.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] For Windows 7, the KB2990941 update is required for this functionality and needs to be integrated into Windows Setup using DISM if Windows 7 has to be installed on the NVMe SSD.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Windows 8/8.1 also supports the SCSI unmap command, an analog of SATA TRIM, for USB-attached SSDs or SATA-to-USB enclosures.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] It is also supported over USB Attached SCSI Protocol (UASP).
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] While Windows 7 supported automatic TRIM for internal SATA SSDs, Windows 8.1 and above support manual TRIM as well as automatic TRIM for SATA, NVMe and USB-attached SSDs.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Manual TRIM is accessed through the expanded Windows Defrag utility.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] Solaris as of version 10 Update 6 (released in October 2008), and recent versions of OpenSolaris, Solaris Express Community Edition, Illumos, Linux with ZFS on Linux, and FreeBSD all can use SSDs as a performance booster for ZFS.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] A low-latency SSD can be used for the ZFS Intent Log (ZIL), where it is named the SLOG.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] An SSD may also be used for the level 2 Adaptive Replacement Cache (L2ARC), which is used to cache data for reading.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] ZFS for FreeBSD introduced support for TRIM on September 23, 2012.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] The Unix File System also supports the TRIM command.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] The following are noted standardization organizations and bodies that work to create standards for solid-state drives (and other computer storage devices).
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] The table below also includes organizations which promote the use of solid-state drives.
[src:block-storage/solid-state-drive] This is not necessarily an exhaustive list.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] A **storage area network** (**SAN**) or **storage network** is a computer network which provides access to consolidated, block-level data storage.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] SANs are primarily used to access data storage devices, such as disk arrays and tape libraries from servers so that the devices appear to the operating system as direct-attached storage.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] A SAN typically is a dedicated network of storage devices not accessible through the local area network (LAN).
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] Although a SAN provides only block-level access, file systems built on top of SANs do provide file-level access and are known as shared-disk file systems.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] Newer SAN configurations enable hybrid SAN and allow traditional block storage that appears as local storage but also object storage for web services through APIs.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] Storage area networks (SANs) are sometimes referred to as *network behind the servers* and historically developed out of a centralized data storage model, but with its own data network.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] A SAN is, at its simplest, a dedicated network for data storage.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] In addition to storing data, SANs allow for the automatic backup of data, and the monitoring of the storage as well as the backup process.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] A SAN is a combination of hardware and software.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] It grew out of data-centric mainframe architectures, where clients in a network can connect to several servers that store different types of data.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] To scale storage capacities as the volumes of data grew, direct-attached storage (DAS) was developed, where disk arrays or just a bunch of disks (JBODs) were attached to servers.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] In this architecture, storage devices can be added to increase storage capacity.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] However, the server through which the storage devices are accessed is a single point of failure, and a large part of the LAN network bandwidth is used for accessing, storing and backing up data.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] To solve the single point of failure issue, a *direct-attached shared storage* architecture was implemented, where several servers could access the same storage device.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] DAS was the first network storage system and is still widely used where data storage requirements are not very high.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] Out of it developed the network-attached storage (NAS) architecture, where one or more dedicated file server or storage devices are made available in a LAN.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] Therefore, the transfer of data, particularly for backup, still takes place over the existing LAN.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] If more than a terabyte of data was stored at any one time, LAN bandwidth became a bottleneck.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] Therefore, SANs were developed, where a dedicated storage network was attached to the LAN, and terabytes of data are transferred over a dedicated high speed and bandwidth network.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] Within the SAN, storage devices are interconnected.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] Transfer of data between storage devices, such as for backup, happens behind the servers and is meant to be transparent.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] In a NAS architecture data is transferred using the TCP and IP protocols over Ethernet.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] Distinct protocols were developed for SANs, such as Fibre Channel, iSCSI, Infiniband.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] Therefore, SANs often have their own network and storage devices, which have to be bought, installed, and configured.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] This makes SANs inherently more expensive than NAS architectures.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] SANs have their own networking devices, such as SAN switches.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] To access the SAN, so-called SAN servers are used, which in turn connect to SAN host adapters.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] Within the SAN, a range of data storage devices may be interconnected, such as SAN-capable disk arrays, JBODs and tape libraries.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] Servers that allow access to the SAN and its storage devices are said to form the *host layer* of the SAN.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] Such servers have host adapters, which are cards that attach to slots on the server motherboard (usually PCI slots) and run with a corresponding firmware and device driver.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] Through the host adapters the operating system of the server can communicate with the storage devices in the SAN.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] In Fibre channel deployments, a cable connects to the host adapter through the gigabit interface converter (GBIC).
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] GBICs are also used on switches and storage devices within the SAN, and they convert digital bits into light impulses that can then be transmitted over the Fibre Channel cables.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] Conversely, the GBIC converts incoming light impulses back into digital bits.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] The predecessor of the GBIC was called gigabit link module (GLM).
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] The fabric layer consists of SAN networking devices that include SAN switches, routers, protocol bridges, gateway devices, and cables.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] SAN network devices move data within the SAN, or between an *initiator*, such as an HBA port of a server, and a *target*, such as the port of a storage device.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] When SANs were first built, hubs were the only devices that were Fibre Channel capable, but Fibre Channel switches were developed and hubs are now rarely found in SANs.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] Switches have the advantage over hubs that they allow all attached devices to communicate simultaneously, as a switch provides a dedicated link to connect all its ports with one another.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] When SANs were first built, Fibre Channel had to be implemented over copper cables, these days multimode optical fibre cables are used in SANs.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] SANs are usually built with redundancy, so SAN switches are connected with redundant links.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] SAN switches connect the servers with the storage devices and are typically non-blocking allowing transmission of data across all attached wires at the same time.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] SAN switches are for redundancy purposes set up in a meshed topology.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] A single SAN switch can have as few as 8 ports and up to 32 ports with modular extensions.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] So-called director-class switches can have as many as 128 ports.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] In switched SANs, the Fibre Channel switched fabric protocol FC-SW-6 is used under which every device in the SAN has a hardcoded World Wide Name (WWN) address in the host bus adapter (HBA).
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] If a device is connected to the SAN its WWN is registered in the SAN switch name server.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] In place of a WWN, or worldwide port name (WWPN), SAN Fibre Channel storage device vendors may also hardcode a worldwide node name (WWNN).
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] The ports of storage devices often have a WWN starting with 5, while the bus adapters of servers start with 10 or 21.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] The serialized Small Computer Systems Interface (SCSI) protocol is often used on top of the Fibre Channel switched fabric protocol in servers and SAN storage devices.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] The Internet Small Computer Systems Interface (iSCSI) over Ethernet and the Infiniband protocols may also be found implemented in SANs, but are often bridged into the Fibre Channel SAN.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] However, Infiniband and iSCSI storage devices, in particular, disk arrays, are available.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] The various storage devices in a SAN are said to form the *storage layer*.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] It can include a variety of hard disk and magnetic tape devices that store data.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] In SANs, disk arrays are joined through a RAID which makes a lot of hard disks look and perform like one big storage device.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] Every storage device, or even partition on that storage device, has a logical unit number (LUN) assigned to it.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] Every node in the SAN, be it a server or another storage device, can access the storage by referencing the LUN.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] The LUNs allow for the storage capacity of a SAN to be segmented and for the implementation of access controls.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] A particular server, or a group of servers, may, for example, be only given access to a particular part of the SAN storage layer, in the form of LUNs.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] When a storage device receives a request to read or write data, it will check its access list to establish whether the node, identified by its LUN, is allowed to access the storage area, also identified by a LUN.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] LUN masking is a technique whereby the host bus adapter and the SAN software of a server restrict the LUNs for which commands are accepted.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] In doing so LUNs that should never be accessed by the server are masked.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] Another method to restrict server access to particular SAN storage devices is fabric-based access control, or zoning, which is enforced by the SAN networking devices and servers.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] Under zoning, server access is restricted to storage devices that are in a particular SAN zone.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] Storage networks may also be built using Serial Attached SCSI (SAS) and Serial ATA (SATA) technologies.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] SAS evolved from SCSI direct-attached storage.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] SATA evolved from Parallel ATA direct-attached storage.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] SAS and SATA devices can be networked using SAS expanders.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] The Storage Networking Industry Association (SNIA) defines a SAN as "a network whose primary purpose is the transfer of data between computer systems and storage elements".
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] But a SAN does not just consist of a communication infrastructure, it also has a software *management layer*.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] This software organizes the servers, storage devices, and the network so that data can be transferred and stored.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] Because a SAN does not use direct attached storage (DAS), the storage devices in the SAN are not owned and managed by a server.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] A SAN allows a server to access a large data storage capacity and this storage capacity may also be accessible by other servers.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] Moreover, SAN software must ensure that data is directly moved between storage devices within the SAN, with minimal server intervention.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] SAN management software is installed on one or more servers and management clients on the storage devices.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] Two approaches have developed in SAN management software: in-band and out-of-band management.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] In-band means that management data between server and storage devices is transmitted on the same network as the storage data.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] While out-of-band means that management data is transmitted over dedicated links.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] SAN management software will collect management data from all storage devices in the storage layer.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] This includes info on read and write failures, storage capacity bottlenecks and failure of storage devices.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] SAN management software may integrate with the Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP).
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] In 1999 Common Information Model (CIM), an open standard, was introduced for managing storage devices and to provide interoperability, The web-based version of CIM is called Web-Based Enterprise Management (WBEM) and defines SAN storage device objects and process transactions.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] Use of these protocols involves a CIM object manager (CIMOM), to manage objects and interactions, and allows for the central management of SAN storage devices.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] Basic device management for SANs can also be achieved through the Storage Management Interface Specification (SMI-S), were CIM objects and processes are registered in a directory.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] Software applications and subsystems can then draw on this directory.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] Management software applications are also available to configure SAN storage devices, allowing, for example, the configuration of zones and LUNs.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] Ultimately SAN networking and storage devices are available from many vendors and every SAN vendor has its own management and configuration software.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] Common management in SANs that include devices from different vendors is only possible if vendors make the application programming interface (API) for their devices available to other vendors.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] In such cases, upper-level SAN management software can manage the SAN devices from other vendors.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] In a SAN, data is transferred, stored and accessed on a block level.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] As such, a SAN does not provide data file abstraction, only block-level storage and operations.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] Server operating systems maintain their own file systems on their own dedicated, non-shared LUNs on the SAN, as though they were local to themselves.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] If multiple systems were simply to attempt to share a LUN, these would interfere with each other and quickly corrupt the data.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] Any planned sharing of data on different computers within a LUN requires software.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] File systems have been developed to work with SAN software to provide file-level access.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] These are known as shared-disk file system.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] Video editing systems require very high data transfer rates and very low latency.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] SANs in media and entertainment are often referred to as serverless due to the nature of the configuration which places the video workflow (ingest, editing, playout) desktop clients directly on the SAN rather than attaching to servers.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] Control of data flow is managed by a distributed file system.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] Per-node bandwidth usage control, sometimes referred to as quality of service (QoS), is especially important in video editing as it ensures fair and prioritized bandwidth usage across the network.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] SAN Storage QoS enables the desired storage performance to be calculated and maintained for network customers accessing the device.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] Alternatively, over-provisioning can be used to provide additional capacity to compensate for peak network traffic loads.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] However, where network loads are not predictable, over-provisioning can eventually cause all bandwidth to be fully consumed and latency to increase significantly resulting in SAN performance degradation.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] Storage virtualization is the process of abstracting logical storage from physical storage.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] The physical storage resources are aggregated into storage pools, from which the logical storage is created.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] It presents to the user a logical space for data storage and transparently handles the process of mapping it to the physical location, a concept called location transparency.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] This is implemented in modern disk arrays, often using vendor-proprietary technology.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] However, the goal of storage virtualization is to group multiple disk arrays from different vendors, scattered over a network, into a single storage device.
[src:block-storage/storage-area-network] The single storage device can then be managed uniformly.
